  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe miscompile arises when
transforming a logical-select form of a floating-point range check expressed as:
select %cmp2, %cmp1, false, where %cmp2 is (fcmp ogt x, -C) and %cmp1 is (fcmp
ninf olt x, C). InstCombine recognizes the pattern (X < C) && (X > -C) and
rewrites it to fabs(X) < C. However, in the original IR, the 'ninf' fast-math
flag applies only to %cmp1. Because %cmp1 produces poison when X = -inf, that
poison is never observed if %cmp2 is false. The select is poison-safe in this
case because the poisoned value is in the unchosen arm. After transformation, the
fabs and the single fcmp inherit the union of fast-math flags (including 'ninf'),
so the transformed code asserts that X is not infinite unconditionally. For X =
-inf, this causes fabs(x) to become poison and the fcmp result to be poison,
making the target more poisonous than the source. Alive2 shows exactly this with
x = -inf.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows InstCombine folding the
select into an fcmp after inserting a fabs intrinsic with the 'ninf' flag: %1 =
call ninf float @llvm.fabs.f32(float %x); %cond = fcmp ninf olt float %1, C. The
first transformation point is foldBooleanAndOr -> foldLogicOfFCmps. The
range-check canonicalization at lines 1505-1541 in InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp is
applied. Unlike earlier combining logic (lines ~1438-1455) which intersects FMF
for logical selects, this range-check transform unconditionally unions fast-math
flags (lines 1534-1535). That is inconsistent with the requirement stated at
lines 3522-3524: logical and/or (from select) must be poison-safe.\n\n3. Root
Cause Analysis:\nIn foldLogicOfFCmps, the range-check canonicalization block
(lines 1505-1541) sets Builder fast-math flags to LHS->FMF | RHS->FMF regardless
of IsLogicalSelect. When only one side has a restrictive flag (e.g., ninf), union
propagates that assumption to the new fused operation, strengthening
preconditions and enabling new poison that could not occur along the actually
selected path of the original select. For logical selects, we must not introduce
new assumptions that can create poison that was previously masked. The correct
behavior is to intersect FMF for poison safety (only assumptions common to both
operands) or otherwise bail out. Other parts of the function already use
intersection when IsLogicalSelect is true (e.g., identical operand fold). The
lack of an IsLogicalSelect check here is the bug.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Points(s):\nEdit lines 1534-1535 in
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp.\nChange from
unconditional union of fast-math flags to conditional: use intersection if
IsLogicalSelect, otherwise keep union. This preserves existing optimization for
non-logical cases while ensuring poison safety for logical-select-derived
AND/OR.\nPatch concept:\nReplace:\n
Builder.setFastMathFlags(LHS->getFastMathFlags() |
RHS->getFastMathFlags());\nWith:\n  FastMathFlags FMFL =
LHS->getFastMathFlags();\n  FastMathFlags FMFR = RHS->getFastMathFlags();\n
FastMathFlags FMF = IsLogicalSelect ? (FMFL & FMFR) : (FMFL | FMFR);\n
Builder.setFastMathFlags(FMF);\nThis uses existing FastMathFlags operators (& and
|) consistent with prior code usage.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe transformation
incorrectly unions fast-math flags in a context that must be poison-safe (logical
select lowering). Intersecting the flags avoids introducing new assumptions (like
ninf) that broaden poison conditions. The fix adjusts fast-math flag propagation
for the range-check -> fabs fold when IsLogicalSelect is true. This restores
correctness and eliminates the miscompile demonstrated by Alive2.\n",
